What would happen if you used notify() instead of notifyAll()? Why might this cause problems?
  If you have multiple producers and multiple consumers, notify() wakes up only one randomly chosen waiting thread. A producer might 
  accidentally wake up another producer instead of a consumer. If the buffer is full, the awakened producer will just go back to sleep, and 
  the system could deadlock because the consumers were never notified. notifyAll() is safer because it wakes up everyone, ensuring the right 
  type of thread gets a chance to proceed.

Why must wait() be called inside a while loop rather than an if statement? What problem does this solve?
  When a thread wakes up from wait(), it does not immediately execute; it must first re-acquire the lock. By the time it gets the lock, 
  another thread might have already changed the state of the buffer. Additionally, threads can experience "spurious wakeups". The while loop 
  forces the thread to re-verify the condition before continuing.

What would happen if the produce() method wasn't synchronized? Could two producers add items at the same time? 
  Yes, a "race condition" would occur. Two producers could check the buffer size simultaneously, see that there is space, and then both 
  attempt to add an item at the same time. This could result in overwritten data, an IndexOutOfBoundsException, or the buffer exceeding its 
  maximum capacity.

What happens if you forget to call notifyAll() in the produce() method? How would this affect the consumer thread? 
  If the buffer starts empty, the consumer will call wait() and go to sleep. If the producer adds items but never calls notifyAll(), the 
  consumer will never be signaled to wake up. The consumer will sleep infinitely, resulting in a deadlock once the producer eventually fills 
  the buffer and goes to sleep as well.

Why does wait() release the lock? What would happen if it didn't? 
  If a thread went to sleep while holding the lock, no other thread would ever be able to access the synchronized methods. For example, 
  if a consumer sees an empty buffer and goes to sleep holding the lock, the producer could never enter the produce() method to add items. 
  The entire application would instantly deadlock.
